## 3. The SR constant-K_G slice (what the substrate encodes when K_G doesn't vary)

SR has K_G ≈ 1.0 across all 137 rows (range 6.3e-4 from numerical noise). On this constant-K_G slice, every candidate substrate observable **varies**:

| Candidate | Varies on SR slice? |
|---|---|
| `ulp_spread_log2` | VARIES |
| `log2_min_ulp` | VARIES |
| `log2_base_operand_ulp` | VARIES |
| `log2_x_term_ulp` | VARIES |
| `signed_asymmetry` | VARIES |
| `E_log2_base_operand` | VARIES |

**What the substrate is encoding** when K_G doesn't change: **coordinate position along the surface**. As β sweeps from 0.01 to 0.97, base_operand sweeps from ~1 to ~0.06; E sweeps from 0 to −4. K_G stays at 1.0 throughout. The substrate sees something K_G doesn't.

This confirms the **finer-than-K_G** reading of the substrate encoding. It carries (K_G-like information) × (coordinate-position information). When K_G changes, the K_G-like piece tracks it perfectly (ρ = −1.0 in Schwarzschild + pure_algebraic). When K_G is constant, the coordinate-position piece varies freely.

