## 4. Cross-fixture comparison at matched K_G

10 matched-K_G pairs were found between Schwarzschild and pure_algebraic (K_G within 1% relative tolerance). For each pair, signature-match checked across all 6 candidates:

| Candidate | Match rate across 5 sampled pairs |
|---|---|
| `E_log2_base_operand` | 0/5 (always differs) |
| `log2_base_operand_ulp` | 1/5 |
| `log2_min_ulp` | 1/5 |
| `signed_asymmetry` | 1/5 |
| `ulp_spread_log2` | 1/5 |
| `log2_x_term_ulp` | **5/5** (consistently matches) |

**Cross-fixture encoding is fixture-bound for E and most candidates.** The exception is `log2_x_term_ulp` — the ulp of the x_term operand consistently matches across fixtures at matched K_G. This makes physical sense: at matched K_G, the curve is at a matched proximity to the singular boundary, so `base_operand` is similar (1-x_term in both forms), so `x_term` is similar, so `ulp(x_term)` is similar.

**E does NOT match cross-fixture** because base_operand IS similar but the *log2* of similar values can differ by O(1) if they're near a binade boundary. So E captures finer-grained position than `log2_x_term_ulp`.

